observations.recommendation:
We recommended and the LCE agreed to:
Instruct the MPIDC to conduct physical count of all properties of the MGPD and submit the corresponding RPCPPE and thereafter, reconcile the RPCPPE with the accounting records;
Mobilize additional competent personnel from other departments to assist and facilitate the completion of the physical count of all PPE items;
Reassign the personnel whose plantilla items were under the MGSO to perform their mandated functions particularly the maintenance of complete and updated PCs for control purposes;
Require the Municipal Accounting Office (MAO) to prepare and maintain the Real Property Ledger Cards and CIP Ledger Cards;
Require the MAO and the MGSO to strengthen controls on handling and recording procedures for PPE accounts by performing periodic reconciliation of records, and ensuring that discrepancies noted are immediately investigated and adjusted accordingly in the books; and
Avail the one-time cleansing of PPE accounts provided under COA Circular No. 2020-006 relative to the conduct of physical count of PPE, recognition of PPE items found at station, and disposition for non-existing/missing PPE items.

We recommended and LCE agreed to:
Designate a GSO and require him/her to submit the SSMIs of the issued inventories to the MA for the latter to draw the necessary JEV dropping the subject inventories from the books of accounts;
Recall the personnel under the GS Office and require them to function based on their original plantilla items; and
The GSO and the MA to reconcile their respective Inventory records in accordance with Section 114 of the Manual on the NGAS for LGUs, Volume I to capture all procurements and issuances of inventories for proper recording and presentation in the FS;
We also recommended and the LCE agreed to direct the MPIDC to conduct physical count of supplies and other inventory items and prepare the corresponding report thereon as prescribed by Section 124 of the Manual on the NGAS for LGUs.

We recommended and Management agreed to:
Intensify the tax dissemination/campaign by sending MTO personnel to barangay especially during barangay assemblies for tax information drive to encourage more taxpayers to pay taxes on time;
Issue demand letters to all delinquent taxpayers to settle immediately their unpaid taxes;
Require the MTO to post in conspicuous places and publicly accessible places within the municipality the tax information and send out notices to taxpayers as part of the tax campaign; and
Prioritize the updating of RPT records by providing enough manpower and equipment to MTO so that the said Office will be able to prepare all the needed reports for the establishment and collection of RPT and SET Receivables.

We recommended and the LCE agreed to:
Require the HRMO to assess its existing Organizational Structure, expedite filling up the vacant positions thru advertisement and assessment of qualified employees for promotion, and submit a report thereon to the LCE for approval by appropriate bodies;
Develop a standard process in evaluating the workforce versus functions to determine the need to hire and the number of casuals/JO personnel to be hired;
Limit the hiring of JO personnel to those extremely necessary and deploy to offices that are actually in need of their services; and
Provide guidelines that will facilitate the fair selection and hiring of JO personnel as well as the evaluation of their performance prior to the renewal of their contracts.

We recommended and the LCE agreed to:
Require the HRMO to submit to the MAO the lacking Pag-IBIG numbers of the JO personnel with unremitted contributions.  Otherwise, require the JO employees to apply for Pag-IBIG MID and inform immediately the MAO for remittance purposes;
Return to the JO personnel the previous years’ deducted Pag-IBIG contributions;
Require the MA to facilitate the reconciliation of the amounts withheld and remitted to determine the actual amounts due.  Thereafter, prepare the necessary adjusting entry to correct the Due to Pag-IBIG account; and
Comply religiously with existing laws, rules and regulations on deductions and remittance of HDMF contributions in accordance with the provisions of RA No. 9679.

We recommended that Management:
Instruct the Inventory Committee to conduct physical count of all properties of the MGPD and submit the corresponding RPCPPE;
Thereafter, reconcile the RPCPPE with the accounting records;
Mobilize additional competent personnel from other departments to assist and facilitate the completion of the physical count of all PPE items;
Require the MGSO to maintain complete and updated PCs for control purposes;
Strengthen controls on handling and recording procedures for PPE accounts by performing periodic reconciliation of records, and ensure that discrepancies noted are immediately investigated and adjusted in the books accordingly; and
Avail the one-time cleansing of PPE accounts provided under COA Circular No. 2020-006 relative to the conduct of physical count of PPE, recognition of PPE items found at station, and disposition for non-existing/missing PPE items.

We recommended and Management agreed to require the:
MAO, MGSO and the Municipal Engineer’s Office to prepare and submit the necessary reports and records pertaining to local road network in accordance with the prescribed formats as provided under COA Circular No. 2015-008;
MA and the MGS Officer to conduct regular reconciliation of LRNLCs and the LRNPCs at least on semestral basis;
Municipal Engineer to furnish the MA and the MGS Officer with complete description and cost segregation of various road components for completed road projects as basis for recording in their respective records; and
MA to disclose the total road network in the Notes to the FS as per Annex B of the aforesaid circular.

We commended Management in carrying out measures for timely liquidation of the CAs granted to officials and employees.
Likewise, we recommended and Management agreed to direct the:
MA or other official to follow-up the result of the request for relief of accountability from COA to determine the subsequent action to be done by the MGPD regarding the CA reported as stolen;
MA to issue demand letters to concerned AOs to settle immediately their outstanding CAs;
Verify in the previous years’ records, the entries pertaining to CAs with negative balances and effect the necessary adjustments, if any.  Otherwise, adjust altogether the minimal negative amounts by debiting Advances to Officers and Employees and crediting Prior Years Adjustment to restore the correct balance of the former account;
Comply strictly with the requirements of Section 89 of PD No. 1445 and COA Circular Nos. 97-002 and 2012-001 and all other related rules and regulations pertaining to the grant, utilization and liquidation of CA; and
Continue the good practice of monitoring the CAs granted to officials and employees to ensure timely liquidation thereof.

We recommended and Management agreed to:
Review the computation of premium contributions deducted from the employees’ salaries;
Compare rates and base amounts used in the computation of premium contributions deducted from the employees’ salaries to the rates and base amounts used by the GSIS;
Coordinate with the GSIS the changes in the employee records, salary or status of employment, if any; and
Remit to the GSIS all of the outstanding balance due to the said agency. Otherwise, refund excess amounts of deductions to the employees concerned, if warranted.

We recommended that Management:

Exert utmost effort in tracing the discrepancies between the recorded amount per RPCPPE and per book and adjust the corresponding records to come up with the corrected amounts in the FS;


Determine or assign value to the serviceable properties identified during the physical count but has no corresponding value or records in the Accounting books or in the GSO records; 


Prepare/update the records of PPE accounts and PAR/ARE so that Management may be able to determine the person responsible/liable therefrom; and

Consider the provision of COA Circular No. 2020-006 on the conduct of physical count of PPE, recognition of PPE items found at station, and disposition for non-existing/missing PPE items, for the one-time cleansing of PPE accounts balance of the LGU.

We recommended that Management:

Prioritize the land that need an immediate proof of ownership in CY 2021 and thereafter, until all of the land owned by the Municipality have Torrens Title considering the limited source of fund;

Allocate budget for the cost of processing and securing Torrens Title for the land owned by the Municipality;


Designate a person who will be responsible for the processing of documents relative to securing of Torrens Title; and


Ensure proper safekeeping of the newly secured and subsequently acquired Torrens Titles.

We recommended that Management:

Require the Municipal Accountant to verify in the previous years’ records, the entries pertaining to cash advances with negative balances and effect the necessary adjustments, if any;

Require the Municipal Accountant to issue demand letters compelling the concerned officials or employees to immediately settle in full their outstanding cash advances, either by liquidation, by payment/refund or through salary deductions, whichever is applicable;

Direct all the concerned accountable officials and employees to liquidate/settle their cash advances immediately; and

Strictly comply with the requirements of Section 89 of PD No. 1445 and COA Circular Nos. 97-002 and 2012-001 and all other related rules and regulations pertaining to the grant, utilization and liquidation of cash advances.

We recommended that Management:
Require the Municipal Accountant to effect the proposed adjusting entry to correct the accounting errors made as follows;



Require the Municipal Accountant to review available accounting records pertaining to the negative amounts included in the Due to NGAs account and reconcile the same with the records of the MPDC;

Effect the necessary transfer of funds from the MDF to Trust Fund, if warranted;

Make a representation or confirm from the SAs as to whether or not the balance of the funds transferred to the Municipality with completed PPAs should be returned or be utilized by the LGU;

Determine the PPAs to be appropriated with the fund transfers received by the Municipality as awards in accordance with the pertinent guidelines issued by the agencies that gave the same;

Require the Municipal Accountant to exert effort to properly identify the sources and status of implementation of the related PPAs for the funds transferred by NGAs and prepare a comprehensive schedule for the same; and

Return the said unutilized funds to the Bureau of the Treasury, if the documents or records of the specific accounts could no longer be located or traced.

